{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774541436,"nonce":"b6t4aghtq487bUJ6mbMhK29Ghms=","message":"**Vanilla RNN diagnostic (2026-03-26 ~15:50 UTC)**\n\nSetup: LeakyRNNCell (alpha=1.0, pure vanilla RNN with tanh nonlinearity, no gating), minimax adversarial training, single + population-based (K=5), 5 vmapped replicates, evaluated at batch 499 checkpoint.\n\nResults:\n- vanilla_single: vel(S=0)=0.4245±0.0556, vel(S=1)=0.4245±0.0556, Δvel=0.00%\n- vanilla_pop5:   vel(S=0)=0.4008±0.0554, vel(S=1)=0.4008±0.0554, Δvel=0.00%\n- max_dist: 0.33-0.36/0.50 (weaker reaching than GRU)\n\nConclusion: Removing GRU gating did NOT produce SISU velocity effect. The gating-laziness hypothesis is NOT confirmed — the problem is deeper than the update gate mechanism. Both architectures produce zero SISU sensitivity at the trajectory level.\n\nThis rules out approach 4d (vanilla RNN) and strongly suggests that approach 4e (frozen update gate ablation) would also fail. The issue is not that the GRU can ignore SISU via its update gate — even without gating, the network ignores SISU.\n\nRemaining Tier 1: B (multiplicative SISU gating). This attacks a different hypothesis — not that the network CAN ignore SISU (it can, with any architecture), but that the additive input pathway is too weak to modulate trajectory-level behavior. Multiplicative gating would force SISU to modulate neural gains directly.","files":null}]}